Phase 2 — Functionality Summary (by topic)
Error handling — API contract

All error responses return one JSON shape (ApiErrorResponse): timestamp (UTC), status, code, message, path.
No stack traces are ever returned to clients; details stay server-side.

Error handling — Security layer (before controllers)

401 UNAUTHENTICATED via RestAuthenticationEntryPoint: returned when the request has no valid authenticated user (not logged in / missing or invalid credentials).
403 FORBIDDEN via RestAccessDeniedHandler: returned when the request is authenticated but the user lacks permission/role for the action.
Purpose: ensure /api/** returns JSON errors instead of HTML redirects when security blocks access.

Error handling — Controller/service layer (business rules)

DomainException hierarchy represents business-rule failures and is translated to ApiErrorResponse centrally:

EntityNotFoundException: required entity missing (e.g., employee/document/training not found).
InactiveEntityException: entity exists but is inactive (soft-deleted) and operation requires active.
ImmutableRecordException: attempted modification of immutable records (e.g., training instance/document version).
InvalidTrainingException: training issuance rules violated (e.g., non-current document version, empty trainees, invalid date rules).


GlobalExceptionHandler (@RestControllerAdvice) maps:

validation failures (@Valid) → 400 VALIDATION_FAILED
DomainException → configured 4xx + domain ErrorCode
unexpected exceptions → 500 INTERNAL_ERROR with safe client message



Logging — traceability & audit support

MDC (Mapped Diagnostic Context) keys used: requestId, user, path.
LoggingContextFilter sets MDC values at request start and clears MDC in finally to prevent thread reuse leakage.
logback-spring.xml enforces log format in UTC and prints MDC fields on every log line for correlation and audit tracing.